'''Ryan M. Hanigan''' (born August 16, 1980) is a [[professional baseball]] player for the [[Cincinnati Reds]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Hanigan was born on August 16, 1980, in [[Washington, D.C.]]. After graduating from [[Andover High School (Massachusetts)|Andover High School]] in 1999, Hanigan attended [[Rollins College]], where he signed as an undrafted free agent with the Reds.

Hanigan, a [[catcher]], spent the 2002 to 2006 seasons with Reds [[minor league baseball]] teams. He made his MLB debut on September 9, 2007 as a [[pinch hitter]], and recorded his first major league [[Hit (baseball)|hit]] in that [[at-bat]]. {{as of|2012|6|3}}, Hanigan has a career [[batting average]] of .277, with 17 [[home run]]s and 98 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) over 319 [[games played]].

==Early life==
Hanigan was born on August 16, 1980, in Washington, D.C., to Mike and Helen Hanigan. He had one sibling, an older sister named Hayley.<ref name="Personal">{{cite news|title=Dream come true: Andover's Hanigan making his mark in the major leagues|url=http://www.andovertownsman.com/sports/x645341336/Dream-come-true-Andovers-Hanigan-making-his-mark-in-the-major-leagues|newspaper=Andover Townsman|publisher=Community Newspaper Holdings|last=Willis|first=David|date=September 19, 2007|accessdate=May 26, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/query?id=1338044408725808|archivedate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> He played [[American Legion Baseball]] for American Legion Post 8 in Andover.<ref name="Chance">{{cite news|title=Hanigan works for his chance|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7854969.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 5, 2004|accessdate=May 26, 2012|last=Forsberg|first=Chris}} {{subscription required}}</ref> At Andover High School, Hanigan was a three-year varsity starter, and was named an ''[[The Eagle-Tribune|Eagle-Tribune]]'' and Eastern Massachusetts all-star during his senior season, in which he hit .397.<ref name="Personal" /> From 1997<U+2013>98, the Andover team had a 38<U+2013>9 record.<ref name="Teammate">{{cite news|title=Reds catcher Hanigan gives Oppenheim inspiration|url=http://www.eagletribune.com/local/x1071086536/Reds-catcher-Hanigan-gives-Oppenheim-inspiration/print|newspaper=The Eagle-Tribune|publisher=Community Newspaper Holdings|last=Longo|first=Hector|date=November 14, 2010|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> He was teammates with future professional golfer [[Rob Oppenheim]], and graduated from the school in 1999.<ref name="Teammate" /><ref name="Boston">{{cite news|title=Chasing success|url=http://www.boston.com/yourtown/danvers/articles/2011/03/31/chasing_success/|newspaper=The Boston Globe|publisher=The New York Times Company|last=Mullen|first=Maureen|date=March 31, 2011|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref>

==Career==
===Rollins College===
After graduating from high school, Hanigan had a difficult time finding a college that would let him play baseball.<ref name="Dayton">{{cite news|title=Dragons Insider; Hanigan Cashes in on Opportunity|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11892396.html|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|publisher=Cox Enterprises|date=June 21, 2003|accessdate=May 26, 2012|last=Katz|first=Marc}} {{subscription required}}</ref> He attended Rollins College in [[Winter Park, Florida]], where he played [[third base]] or [[left field]] because of an upperclassman at the [[catcher]] position.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notes: Jorgensen suspended|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070907&content_id=2194562&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|work=MLB.com|date=September 7, 2007|last=Sheldon|first=Mark|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> During the summer in 2001, Hanigan played in the [[New England Collegiate Baseball League]], where he hit .282 in 38 games.<ref name="MLB_Profile">{{cite web|title=Ryan Hanigan|url=http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=452672#gameType=%27R%27|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|work=MLB.com|accessdate=May 26, 2012}} Click on "Bio" for more information</ref> In his junior year, he hit .384 with 48 RBIs over 57 games for Rollins,<ref name="Personal" /> as the team finished 41<U+2013>16 and clinched a berth to the [[NCAA Division II Baseball Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tradition|url=http://www.rollinssports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=19500&ATCLID=1547215|publisher=Rollins College|accessdate=May 26, 2012|date=May 31, 2006}}</ref> Hanigan would have served as team captain his senior year; when he left Rollins, Hanigan's .359 career batting average was seventh best in school history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tars in the Pros|url=http://www.rollinssports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=19500&ATCLID=1548695|publisher=Rollins College|accessdate=May 26, 2012|date=May 27, 2008}}</ref><ref name="Captain">{{cite news|title=Notebook|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7729728.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=September 8, 2002|accessdate=May 26, 2012|last=Vellante|first=John}} {{subscription required}}</ref>

He played summer baseball in the [[Cape Cod League]] for [[Orleans Firebirds|Orleans Cardinals]], where he was named the Top New England Prospect and an All-Star.<ref name="Chance" /> In August 2002, Hanigan was awarded the Charles F. Moore Sr. award for the most valuable player on the Cardinals team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pitching Himself, Catcher wins Cape Kudos|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7727722.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 11, 2002|accessdate=May 26, 2012|last=Nesbitt|first=Andy}} {{subscription required}}</ref> John Brickley, a [[Scout (sport)|scout]] for the Reds, signed him as a free agent on August 23, although six other teams "showed interest" in signing the catcher.<ref name="Boston" /><ref name="Captain" /><ref name="MLB_Profile" />

===Cincinnati Reds===
In 2002, Hanigan began his career with the Reds when he played in six minor league games for the [[Dayton Dragons]] of the [[Midwest League]], batting .273 with three [[hit (baseball)|hits]].<ref name="Minor">{{cite web|title=Ryan Hanigan Minor League Statistics and History|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=haniga001rya|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> On April 28, 2003, in a game against the [[Quad Cities River Bandits|Quad City River Bandits]], he went 4<U+2013>5 with three RBIs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lewis' Double Essential to Dragons 7<U+2013>4 Victory|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11890494.html|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|publisher=Cox Enterprises|date=April 28, 2003|accessdate=May 27, 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Hanigan was named to the East squad in the Midwest League All-Star Game, where he served as the reserve catcher.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seven Dragons Heading to All-Star Game|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11887948.html|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|publisher=Cox Enterprises|date=June 5, 2003|accessdate=May 27, 2012|last=Albers|first=Bucky}} {{subscription required}}</ref> As a pinch hitter on June 5, 2003, Hanigan hit the game-tying [[single (baseball)|single]] against [[Clinton LumberKings]] to score Luis Bolivar; the Dragons won the game, overcoming an eight-run deficient.<ref>{{cite news|title=Midwest League; Ninth-Inning Rally Boosts Dragons|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11887967.html|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|publisher=Cox Enterprises|date=June 6, 2003|accessdate=May 27, 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Later in July, he was placed on the disabled list (DL) with a [[high ankle sprain]]; to that point, he was hitting .283 with 26 RBIs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dragons Rested; It's Time to Run|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11899023.html|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|publisher=Cox Enterprises|date=July 17, 2003|accessdate=May 27, 2012|last=Katz|first=Marc}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Hanigan finished the season batting .277 with a home run and 31 RBIs, which earned him a promotion to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Louisville Bats]].<ref name="Chance" /><ref name="Minor" /> In one game for the Bats, he went 1<U+2013>3.<ref name="Minor" />

Hanigan spent the entire 2004 season with the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Potomac Nationals|Potomac Cannons]], where he served as the team's catcher and [[designated hitter]].<ref>{{cite news|title=With a Year Under His Belt, Hanigan Has Become a Big Hit|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A30006-2004May15.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post Company|date=May 16, 2004|last=Gouker|first=Dustin|page=E-11|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> From July 6 to July 29, he had a 22-game [[hit streak]], the longest in the [[Carolina League]] for the year.<ref name="MLB_Profile" /> On August 24, he hit in the game-winning run against the [[Salem Red Sox|Salem Avalanche]] with two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannons Elude Avalanche|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-12700564.html|newspaper=The Roanoke Times|publisher=Landmark Media Enterprises|date=August 25, 2004|accessdate=May 27, 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref> For the season, Hanigan hit .296 with five home runs and 56 RBIs over 119 games as the Cannons made the Carolina League Northern Division playoffs for the first time since 1995.<ref name="Minor" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Cannons Silenced In Game 3 Defeat|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A13376-2004Sep11.html?nav=rss_sports/areaproteams/minorleaguebaseball|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post Company|date=September 11, 2004|last=Orton|first=Kathy|page=D12|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref>

The following season Hanigan played for the [[Double-A]] [[Chattanooga Lookouts]]. On August 29, 2005, he hit a [[grand slam]] against the [[Jackson Generals|West Tennessee Diamond Jaxx]] as the Lookouts lost, 10<U+2013>12.<ref name="MLB_Profile" /> After the season, he was selected by the Reds to represent the organization in the [[Arizona Fall League]], and was a [[non-roster invitee]] to the Reds 2006 [[spring training]] camp.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dad Finally gets to see Son Play|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-135509472.html|newspaper=The Cincinnati Post|publisher=E. W. Scripps Company|date=August 25, 2005|accessdate=May 28, 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=National League 40-man rosters |url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/40-man.htm|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=February 17, 2006|accessdate=May 28, 2012}}</ref> In 2006, Hanigan appeared in 56 games for the Lookouts as well as eight games for the Bats. During a July 13, 2006 contest, Hanigan drove in the what would be the winning run with two outs in the seventh inning against the [[Birmingham Barons]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hanigan comes through.|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148196401.html|newspaper=Chattanooga Times Free Press|publisher=WEHCO Media, Inc.|date=July 14, 2006|accessdate=May 28, 2012|last=Paschall|first=David}} {{subscription required}}</ref> For the season, he hit .246 for the Lookouts and .154 for the Bats.<ref name="Minor" />
{{Quote box
 |quote  = "I didn't have any time to waste&nbsp;... I was running in from the bullpen, didn't have a time to get nervous. I tried to enjoy it, pick out a pitch I could handle, put a good swing on it and it all worked out."
 |source = Hanigan on MLB debut<ref name="Hamstring">{{cite news|title=Hamstring keeps Hamilton Out|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-168567950.html|newspaper=The Cincinnati Post|publisher=E. W. Scripps Company|date=September 10, 2007|last=Rosecrans|first=C. Trent|accessdate=May 28, 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref>
