Playing for the Lookouts, Hanigan was selected to the [[Southern League (baseball)|Southern League]] All-Star Game in June 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lookouts trio gets star nods|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-165736694.html|date=June 27, 2007|newspaper=Chattanooga Times Free Press|publisher=WEHCO Media, Inc.|last=Paschall|first=David|accessdate=May 31, 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref> He was promoted to the Bats on June 28, 2007, after reaching base safely in 40 of his last 42 games for the Lookouts, including three four-hit games.<ref name="MLB_Profile" /> He was [[Glossary of baseball (C)#called up|called up]] to the major-league squad on September 1.<ref name="Globe2">{{cite news|title=Notebook|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7601052.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=September 16, 2007|accessdate=May 26, 2012|last=Vellante|first=John}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Hanigan made his MLB debut on September 9; pinch hitting for [[Kirk Saarloos]], he doubled to left field off the first pitch thrown to him by [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] [[Ben Sheets]], and later scored a [[run (baseball)|run]] on a [[wild pitch]].<ref name="Hamstring" /><ref name="Globe2" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Milwaukee Brewers 10, Cincinnati Reds 5|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2007/B09090CIN2007.htm|accessdate=May 30, 2012}}</ref> For the MLB Reds, Hanigan hit .300 in five game played, with two RBIs and a double. During the off-season, he played in the [[Dominican Professional Baseball League]] for the [[Leones del Escogido]].<ref name="MLB_Profile" /> Playing for the Bats in 2008, Hanigan was a mid-season and postseason [[International League]] (IL) All-Star, and was named the best defensive catcher in the IL by ''[[Baseball America]]''.<ref name="MLB_Profile" /> He was called up to the majors on August 10, 2008, after [[David Ross (baseball)|David Ross]] was [[designated for assignment]] by the Reds; 18 days later, he hit a home run in the eighth inning to score what would be the winning run against the [[Houston Astros]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=280826118&prov=ap|title=Arroyo, Hanigan lead Reds to 2-1 win over Astros|last=Duncan|first=Chris|work=Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|date=August 26, 2008|accessdate=June 1, 2012}}</ref> After batting .271 in 31 games for the Reds, Hanigan was ranked as the 16th best [[wikt:prospect|prospect]] in the Reds minor league system by ''Baseball America''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/statistics/players/cards/83074|title=Ryan Hanigan, c, Reds|work=Baseball-America|accessdate=June 1, 2012}}</ref>

Outside of five games for the Triple-A squad, Hanigan spent the entire 2009 season with the Reds. Hanigan served as the backup catcher to [[Ram<U+00F3>n Hern<U+00E1>ndez]] until Hern<U+00E1>ndez underwent knee surgery and was placed on the DL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reds need Hanigan to get out of slump|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-20637097.html|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|publisher=Cox Enterprises|date=August 13, 2009|accessdate=June 2, 2012|last=McCoy|first=Hal}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Hanigan went on the DL after he was hit on the face mask by a foul tip and suffered a concussion; he returned on August 8, 2009.<ref name="MLB_Profile" /> For the season, Hanigan had the best [[fielding percentage]] as a catcher (.998), and the second best [[caught stealing]] percentage (42.9) in the majors.<ref>{{cite web|title=2009 Major League Baseball Fielding Leaders|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2009-fielding-leaders.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=June 2, 2012}}</ref>

On April 3, 2011, he set career records by hitting more than one home run and getting four hits in a single game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=310403117|title=Ryan Hanigan homers twice as Reds bash Brewers, complete sweep|work=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 3, 2012}}</ref> Against [[Chicago Cubs]] pitcher [[Sean Marshall]], Hanigan drove in the tie-breaking run in what was an 8<U+2013>7 win for the Reds on August 7.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hanigans single lifts Reds past Cubs|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-29345073.html|newspaper=Charleston Daily Mail|publisher=The Daily Gazette Company|date=August 8, 2011}} {{subscription required}}</ref> He finished the year batting .267 with an [[on-base percentage]] of .356 and a career-high of six home runs.<ref name="MLB_Profile" /> In 2012, Hanigan split time catching with prospect [[Devin Mesoraco]]; on the year, he is hitting .296 over 33 games played.<ref name="MLB_Profile" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Hanigan not worried about playing time|url=http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120305&content_id=27022400&vkey=news_cin&c_id=cin|date=March 5, 2012|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|last=Sheldon|first=Mark|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>

